feature.name: appSecurityClient-1.0
feature.description: Support for securing the client container runtime environment and applications. This feature enables application security, CSIv2 and SSL on the client.

feature.name: distributedMap-1.0
feature.displayName: Distributed Map interface for Dynamic Caching 1.0
feature.description: This feature provides a local cache service which can be accessed through the DistributedMap API. A default cache is bound in JNDI at "services/cache/distributedmap". Caches can be distributed through addition of a network cache provider such as WebSphere eXtreme Scale.

feature.name: federatedRegistry-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for federation of multiple user registries.

feature.name: jdbc-4.0
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of DataSources to access Databases from applications. Any database that complies with the JDBC 4.0 specification can be used; customized configuration of many specific providers is included. High performance connection pooling is also provided.

feature.name: jdbc-4.2
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of DataSources to access Databases from applications. Any JDBC driver that complies with the JDBC 4.2, 4.1, 4.0, 3.0, or 2.x specification can be used; customized configuration of many specific providers is included. High performance connection pooling is also provided.

feature.name: jdbc-4.3
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of DataSources to access Databases from applications. Any JDBC driver that complies with the JDBC 4.3, 4.2, 4.1, 4.0, 3.0, or 2.x specification can be used; customized configuration of many specific providers is included. High performance connection pooling is also provided.

feature.name: jndi-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the use of Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) to access server configured resources such as DataSources or JMS Connection Factories. It also allows access to Java primitives configured in the server as a jndiEntry.

feature.name: json-1.0
feature.description: This feature provides access to the JavaScript Object Notation (JSON4J) library. The JSON4J library provides a simple Java model for constructing and manipulating data to be rendered as JSON data.

feature.name: jwt-1.0
feature.description: This feature allows the runtime to create JSON Web Tokens(JWT).

kernelFeature.description: This feature provides the Liberty kernel, which makes up the core of the Open Liberty runtime.

feature.name: ldapRegistry-3.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for using an LDAP server as a user registry. Any server that supports LDAP Version 3.0 can be used. Multiple LDAP user registries can be configured and then federated to achieve a single logical user registry view.

feature.name: localConnector-1.0
feature.description: This feature allows the use of a local JMX connector that is built into the JVM to access JMX resources in the server. The JMX connector can only be used on the same host machine by a client that has the same user ID and the same JDK as the server process. It enables local access by JMX clients such as jConsole, or other JMX clients that use the Attach API.

feature.name: monitor-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the Performance Monitoring Infrastructure (PMI) for other features the server is running. Monitoring data is accessible through standard MXBeans; access through the traditional WebSphere Perf MBean can be enabled.

feature.name: requestTiming-1.0
feature.description: Provides warnings and diagnostic info for slow or hung requests.

feature.name: restConnector-2.0
feature.description: A secure, REST administrative connector that can be used locally or remotely using any Java developer kit. This connector enables remote access from a Java client or directly through an HTTPS call. The administrator and reader roles protect the connector. The connector requires TLS to keep the communication confidential. The HTTPS port used by the connector is defined through the default HTTP endpoint. This feature supersedes the restConnector-1.0 feature. It enables the REST handler configuration APIs. When this feature is combined with features supporting configuration validation, the corresponding REST handler validation APIs are enabled.

feature.name: servlet-6.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for HTTP Servlets written to the Jakarta Servlet 6.0 specification. You can package servlets in Jakarta EE specified WAR or EAR files. If servlet security is required, you should also configure an appSecurity feature. Without a security feature, any security constraints for the application are ignored.

feature.name: sessionCache-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables persistence of HTTP sessions using JCache. Persisting HTTP session data using JCache allows for high performance HTTP session persistence without the use of a relational database. Failover of HTTP sessions can be achieved by configuring multiple servers to persist data to the same location.

feature.name: sessionDatabase-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables persistence of HTTP sessions to a datasource using JDBC. Persisting HTTP session data to a database allows recovery of the data after a server restart or unexpected server failure. Failover of HTTP sessions can be achieved by configuring multiple servers to persist data to the same location

feature.name: ssl-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) connections. The secure HTTPS listener is not started unless the ssl-1.0 feature is enabled and a keystore is configured.

feature.name: transportSecurity-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) connections. The secure HTTPS listener is not started unless the transportSecurity-1.0 feature is enabled and a keystore is configured.

feature.name: webCache-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables local caching for web responses. It includes the distributedMap feature and performs automatic caching of web application responses to improve response times and throughput. Applications can include a cache-spec.xml file to customize the response caching. The cache may be distributed through addition of a network cache provider such as WebSphere eXtreme Scale.

feature.name: appAuthentication-3.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for securing the server runtime environment and applications using Jakarta Authentication 3.0 providers

feature.name: appAuthorization-2.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for Jakarta Authorization version 2.1 In order to add the appAuthorization-2.1 feature to your server, you need to add the third party provider which is not a part of the Open Liberty profile.

feature.name: appClientSupport-2.0
feature.displayName: Jakarta Application Client Support for Server 2.0
feature.description: This feature enables the Liberty server to process Jakarta EE client modules and support remote Jakarta EE client containers.

feature.name: appSecurity-5.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for securing the server runtime environment and applications using Jakarta Security 3.0.

feature.name: batch-2.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for Jakarta Batch 2.1.

feature.name: beanValidation-3.0
feature.description: The Jakarta Bean Validation 3.0 specification provides an annotation-based model for validating JavaBeans. It can be used to assert and maintain the integrity of data as it travels through an application. This feature is built on the Hibernate Validator Engine.

feature.name: cdi-4.0
feature.description: The Jakarta Contexts and Dependency Injection 4.0 specification makes it easier to integrate Jakarta EE components of different types. It provides a common mechanism to inject components such as enterprise beans or managed beans into other components such as JSPs or other enterprise beans.

feature.name: concurrent-3.0
feature.description: This feature enables the creation of managed executors that allow applications to submit tasks to run concurrently, with thread context that is managed by the application server.It also enables the creation of managed thread factories to create threads that run with the threadcontext of the component that looks up the managed thread factory.

feature.name: connectors-2.1
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of resource adapters to access Enterprise Information Systems (EIS) from applications. The configuration of a resource adapter also includes the configuration of connection factories, administered objects and activation specifications. Any resource adapter that complies with the Jakarta Connectors 2.1 specification or lower can be used. High performance connection pooling is also provided.

feature.name: enterpriseBeans-4.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Enterprise Beans written to the Jakarta Enterprise Beans 4.0 specification.

feature.name: enterpriseBeansHome-4.0
feature.description: This feature enables the use of home interfaces in Jakarta Enterprise Beans.

feature.name: enterpriseBeansLite-4.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Jakarta Enterprise Beans that are written to the Enterprise Beans Lite subset of the Jakarta Enterprise Beans 4.0 specification.

feature.name: enterpriseBeansPersistentTimer-4.0
feature.description: This feature enables the use of persistent timers in Jakarta Enterprise Beans.

feature.name: enterpriseBeansRemote-4.0
feature.description: This feature enables the use of remote interfaces in Jakarta Enterprise Beans.

feature.name: expressionLanguage-5.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Jakarta Expression Language 5.0.

feature.name: faces-4.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for web applications that use the Jakarta Faces 4.0 framework. This framework simplifies the construction of user interfaces.

feature.name: jakartaee-10.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support the Jakarta EE 10.0 Platform.

feature.name: jakartaeeClient-10.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Jakarta EE 10.0 Application Client.

feature.name: jsonb-3.0
feature.description: The Jakarta API for JSON Binding (JSON-B) feature provides a standard for converting between Java objects and JavaScript Object Notation (JSON).

feature.name: jsonp-2.1
feature.description: The Jakarta API for JSON Processing (JSON-P) feature provides a standardized method for constructing and manipulating data to be rendered in JavaScript Object Notation (JSON).

feature.name: mail-2.1
feature.description: This feature allows applications to use the Jakarta Mail 2.1 API.

feature.name: managedBeans-2.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Managed Beans 2.0 specification. Managed Beans provide a common foundation for different Jakarta EE components types that are managed by a container. Common services provided to Managed Beans include resource injection, lifecycle management and the use of interceptors.

feature.name: mdb-4.0
feature.description: This feature enables the use of Message-Driven Jakarta Enterprise Beans written to the Jakarta Enterprise Beans 4.0 specification. MDBs allow asynchronous processing of messages within a Jakarta EE component.

feature.name: messaging-3.1
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of resource adapters to access messaging systems by using the Jakarta Messaging API. This feature also enables the configuration of Jakarta Messaging connection factories, queues, topics, and activation specifications. Any Jakarta Messaging resource adapter that complies with the Jakarta Connectors 2.1 specification can be used.

feature.name: messagingClient-3.0
feature.description: The messagingClient-3.0 feature provides applications with access to the message queues that are hosted on WebSphere Application Server through the Jakarta Messaging 3.0 API. The messagingClient-3.0 feature is compliant with Jakarta Messaging 3.0 specifications. It enables access to the messaging engine that is enabled through the messagingServer-3.0 feature, and also to the Service Integration Bus that is hosted on a full profile server.

feature.name: messagingSecurity-3.0
feature.description: This feature enables the WebSphere Embedded Messaging Server to authenticate and authorize access from Jakarta Messaging clients.

feature.name: messagingServer-3.0
feature.description: This feature enables an embedded messaging server that is Jakarta Messaging compliant. Applications can send and receive messages by using the messagingClient-3.0 feature.

feature.name: microProfile-6.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support MicroProfile 6.0 for Cloud Native Java.

feature.name: microProfile-6.1
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support MicroProfile 6.1 for Cloud Native Java.

feature.name: mpConfig-3.0
feature.description: The Eclipse MicroProfile Config specification provides a unified mechanism to access configuration, providing a single view of multiple sources.

feature.name: mpConfig-3.1
feature.description: The Eclipse MicroProfile Config specification provides a unified mechanism to access configuration, providing a single view of multiple sources.

feature.name: mpFaultTolerance-4.0
feature.description: This feature supports the MicroProfile Fault Tolerance 4.0 API.

feature.name: mpHealth-4.0
feature.description: This feature provides support for the MicroProfile Health specification.

feature.name: mpJwt-2.1
feature.description: This feature enables web applications or microservices to use the Eclipse MicroProfile JSON Web Token 2.1 specification to authenticate users instead of, or in addition to, the configured user registry.

feature.name: mpMetrics-5.0
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Metrics 5.0 specification for enterprise Java.

feature.name: mpMetrics-5.1
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Metrics 5.1 specification for enterprise Java.

feature.name: mpOpenAPI-3.1
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile OpenAPI specification for enterprise Java.

feature.name: mpRestClient-3.0
feature.description: The MicroProfile Rest Client specification provides a type-safe mechanism for invoking RESTful services.

feature.name: mpTelemetry-1.0
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Telemetry specification for enterprise Java.

feature.name: mpTelemetry-1.1
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Telemetry specification for enterprise Java.

feature.name: pages-3.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for Jakarta Server Pages that are written to the Jakarta Server Pages 3.1 specification. This framework simplifies the construction of user interfaces. Enabling this feature also enables the Jakarta Expression Language version 5.0 feature.

feature.name: persistence-3.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for applications that use application-managed and container-managed persistence. This feature includes Jakarta Persistence 3.1 specification interfaces and container-managed persistence integration. EclipseLink is also included as the default persistence provider implementation.

feature.name: persistenceContainer-3.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for applications that use application-managed and container-managed persistence. This feature only includes Jakarta Persistence 3.1 specification interfaces and container-managed persistence integration. This feature does not include a Jakarta Persistence provider implementation.

feature.name: restfulWS-3.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for Jakarta RESTful Web Services 3.1. These annotations can be used to define web service clients and endpoints that comply with the REST architectural style. Endpoints are accessed through a common interface that is based on the HTTP standard methods.

feature.name: restfulWSClient-3.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Jakarta RESTful Web Services 3.1 Client API.

feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support the Jakarta EE 10.0 Web Profile.

feature.name: websocket-2.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for WebSocket applications written to the API for the Jakarta WebSocket 2.1 specification.

feature.name: xmlBinding-4.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Jakarta XML Binding 4.0 specification, which provides easy mapping of Java classes to XML documents.

feature.name: xmlWS-4.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Jakarta XML Web Services 4.0. These web services and clients communicate using XML. Annotations can be used to simplify the development of service clients and endpoints.
